{"analysis_index":36,"title":"Station Risk Classification (PWQO Screening, 2024)","analysis_comments":"This station-level table rolls up 2024 PWQMN results into a single screening metric: the fraction of all PWQO-screened analyte results at each station that exceed the applicable PWQO/interim PWQO. Because the denominator is the total count of analyte-results (not sampling events), stations with broader analyte suites (e.g., metals + nutrients + bacteria) will have a more stable overall exceedance rate than stations with sparse coverage.

Tier assignments are driven by summed exceedances across analytes; in practice, frequent drivers in the 2024 dataset are typically Total Phosphorus (30 µg/L river objective), Aluminum (screened only when same-day pH supports evaluation), and Iron (300 µg/L), with E. coli often producing high per-sample exceedance rates (noting the PWQO geometric-mean requirement is not applied here).

Caveats: hardness-adjusted metals (Cd/Cu/Pb) exclude samples lacking same-day hardness, and aluminum excludes samples lacking same-day pH or with pH 5.5–6.5, reducing N for those analytes at some stations.","code_filename":"station_risk_classification_pwqo_2024.py","data_filename":"station_risk_classification_pwqo_2024.csv"}
